g and -- tstylization -- tIntroduction to Part 3 -- tChapter 11. Playing with the voice of the other: -- tStylized Kanaksprak in conversations among German adolescents -- tChapter 12. Identity and language construction in -- tan online community: The case of ‘Ali G’ -- tChapter 13. Positioning in style: Men in women’s -- tjointly produced stories -- tChapter 14. The construction of otherness in -- treported dialogues as a resource for identity work -- tChapter 15. The humorous stylization of ‘new’ women -- tand men and conservative others -- tChapter 16. A postscript: Style and identity in -- tinteractional sociolinguistics -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume presents an interactional perspective on linguistic variability that takes into account the construction of social identities through the formation of social communicative styles. It shows that style is a useful category in bridging the gap between single parameter variation and social identity. Social positioning, i.e., finding one's place in society, is one of its motivating forces. Various aspects of the expression of stylistic features are focused on, from language choice and linguistic variation in a narrow sense to practices of social categorization, pragmatics patterns, preferences for specific communicative genres, rhetorical practices including prosodic features, and aesthetic choices and preferences for specific forms of taste (looks, clothes, music, etc.). These various features of expression are connected to multimodal stylistic indices through talk; thus, styles emerge from discourse. Styles are adapted to changing contexts, and develop in the course of social processes. The analytical perspective chosen proposes an alternative to current approaches to variability under the influence of the so-called variationist paradigm.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World